Delegates are the foundation of C# functional features: LINQ, events, callbacks, and strategy pattern implementations all use them.

```csharp
// Inline delegate (lambda)
Func<int, int> square = x => x * x;
Console.WriteLine(square(5)); // 25

Action<string> log = msg => Console.WriteLine(msg);
log("Hello");
```

Events prevent external code from clearing the invocation list (`= null`) or invoking the event directly — encapsulation for callbacks.

The difference between `delegate` and `Func/Action`: use `Func/Action` for simple callbacks; define a named delegate type when the semantic meaning matters (self-documenting) or when you need special attributes.

